{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585176","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585176"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:05:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14927"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14927","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14927"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.19,0.12,0.54,0.08,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7615"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66014"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7615","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7615"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14927"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51465"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4944"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7882"},{"type":"tags","id":"10765"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18622"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18623"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18625"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66014","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66014"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ECystic fibrosis leads to chronic respiratory infections. One particular bacterial species commonly forms biofilms in the airways of these patients, protected by a characteristic mucoid capsule.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following bacteria produces an alginate capsule that is an important virulence factor in cystic fibrosis lung infections?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Streptococcus pneumoniae","Klebsiella pneumoniae","Pseudomonas aeruginosa","Haemophilus influenzae","Staphylococcus aureus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E produces a distinctive alginate capsule that is crucial for its persistence in cystic fibrosis airways. This capsule enables biofilm formation, protects against host immune responses, and contributes to antibiotic resistance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less relevant because:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E produces a polysaccharide capsule but is not a characteristic pathogen in cystic fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EKlebsiella pneumoniae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E has a capsule made of complex polysaccharides but rarely causes significant infection in cystic fibrosis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can infect cystic fibrosis patients but its capsule is not specifically adapted to this environment\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can cause early infection in cystic fibrosis but does not produce a true capsule\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe mucoid phenotype of \u003Cem\u003EPseudomonas aeruginosa\u003C/em\u003E is a specific adaptation to the cystic fibrosis airway environment and is associated with poor clinical outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Mucoid strains of Pseudomonas aeruginosa with alginate capsules are characteristic colonisers in cystic fibrosis airways.","The alginate capsule of Pseudomonas aeruginosa contributes to biofilm formation and antibiotic resistance in cystic fibrosis.","Chronic Pseudomonas aeruginosa infection is a major cause of morbidity and mortality in cystic fibrosis patients."],"references":["Blanchard AC, Waters VJ. Opportunistic Pathogens in Cystic Fibrosis: Epidemiology and Pathogenesis of Lung Infection. J Pediatric Infect Dis Soc. 2022 Sep 7;11(Supplement_2):S3-S12. doi: 10.1093/jpids/piac052. PMID: 36069904.","Lund-Palau H, Turnbull AR, Bush A, Bardin E, Cameron L, Soren O, Wierre-Gore N, Alton EW, Bundy JG, Connett G, Faust SN, Filloux A, Freemont P, Jones A, Khoo V, Morales S, Murphy R, Pabary R, Simbo A, Schelenz S, Takats Z, Webb J, Williams HD, Davies JC. Pseudomonas aeruginosa infection in cystic fibrosis: pathophysiological mechanisms and therapeutic approaches. Expert Rev Respir Med. 2016 Jun;10(6):685-97. doi: 10.1080/17476348.2016.1177460. Epub 2016 May 13. PMID: 27175979.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Janeway CA Jr, Travers P, Walport M, et al. Immunobiology: The Immune System in Health and Disease. 5th edition. New York: Garland Science; 2001. Generation of lymphocytes in bone marrow and thymus. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK27123/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51465"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14927"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51465"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-28T19:06:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-28T19:08:07+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7615"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66014"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,